    "caption": "Every zebra is wearing a one-of-a-kind outfit.",
    "shortDescription": "Zebras live in big herds and stay close for a very good reason — when a herd bolts together, all those spinning black-and-white stripes create a dizzying pattern that makes it genuinely hard for a predator to lock onto any single animal. A zebra foal learns its mother's stripe pattern in its first hours of life and never forgets it. Fun fact: No two zebras have the same stripe pattern — you could tell every zebra apart the same way you tell faces apart."
